Chop any larger @New Potatoes{2} in half. Place them into a #pot{} of cold water. Add @salt{pinch} and bring to the boil over high heat. Once boiling, reduce the heat to a simmer and cook for ~{15%minutes} or until the potatoes are tender.

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Pick the leaves from the @Lemon Thyme{8}. Place the @British Chicken Thighs{8} on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with a good glug of @olive oil{}, your lemon thyme leaves, a pinch of @salt{} on each, a good grind of @black pepper{} and coat well. Roast for ~{25%minutes} or until it is no longer pink in the middle.

Whilst your chicken and potatoes are cooking, prepare the rest of the dish. For the slaw, peel and chop the top and bottom off the @Carrot{4}, then grate on the coarse side of your #grater{}. Cut the @Red Cabbage{1/2} in half, remove the tough core and cut into ½cm slices (or as a thin as you can).

Place your cabbage in a #bowl{} and season with a good pinch of @salt{pinch} to soften it. After ~{15%minutes}, drain off any liquid from your cabbage and mix in your grated carrot and the @Garlic Mayonnaise{4}.

Pick the @Flat Leaf Parsley{10} leaves and roughly chop. Zest and juice the @Lemon{1}. Mix half your parsley with a pinch of lemon zest, your lemon juice and @Olive Oil{6}(ml) in a small bowl. Add the @Dijon Mustard{1} to taste (start with ½ tsp, mix together and add more if you want). Keep to one side.

When your potatoes are cooked, drain and allow the steam to escape in a #colander{} for ~{1%minute}. Return them to the pot off the heat and crush your potatoes gently with a fork. Mix in your remaining chopped parsley and a splash of olive oil. Season with a pinch of salt and some black pepper if needed.

When your chicken is cooked and whilst still piping hot, smear with a generous amount of your parsley, lemon and mustard marinade. Serve on top of your crushed potatoes with a side of garlicky slaw.

